{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "FIFA said three former top officials arranged to pay themselves more than $80 million over the past five years.", "abstract": "Internal investigation of FIFA, world soccer's governing body, reveals that organization's former top officials Sepp Blatter, Jerome Valcke and Markus Kattner arranged to pay themselves more than $80 million over five years just as scandal began to unfold; also finds that three men modified termination clauses in their employment contracts to ensure that they would receive multimillion-dollar payouts in event they were fired.", "section_name": "Sports", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Sam", "role": "reported", "lastname": "BORDEN", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Andrew", "role": "reported", "lastname": "DAS", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By SAM BORDEN and ANDREW DAS", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/04/sports/soccer/fifa-corruption-sepp-blatter-jerome-valcke.html", "lead_paragraph": "FIFA said three former top officials arranged to pay themselves more than $80 million over the past five years.", "headline": {"main": "Sepp Blatter and Deputies Arranged Huge Payouts After Indictments, FIFA Says", "print_headline": "FIFA Officials Took Big Raises Amid Scandal"}, "_id": "57519f2038f0d86ce33333b1", "word_count": "1275", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/06/04/sports/04fifa-web/04fifa-web-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/06/04/sports/04fifa-web/04fifa-web-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 384, "url": "images/2016/06/04/sports/04fifa-web/04fifa-web-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/06/04/sports/04fifa-web/04fifa-web-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "384"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images